    </activity>
    
    <definition xml:id="vertex-form-of-a-quadratic-function">
      <statement>
        <p> The maximum or minimum of a quadratic function is also known as its <term>vertex</term>. The <term>vertex form</term> <idx><h>quadratic function</h><h>vertex form</h></idx> of a quadratic function is given by <me>f(x)=a(x-h)^2+k</me>, where <m>(h, k)</m> is the <term>vertex</term> <idx><h>quadratic function</h><h>vertex from vertex form</h></idx> of the parabola.</p>  
          <p> Vertex form can be used to identify the <term>axis of symmetry</term>, also known as the line of symmetry (the line that makes the shape of an object symmetrical). For a quadratic function, the axis of symmetry always passes through the vertex <m>(h,k)</m> and so <m>x = h</m> is the axis of symmetry. <idx><h>quadratic function</h><h>axis of symmetry from vertex form</h></idx>
        </p>
      </statement>
    </definition>

    <activity xml:id="PR1-activity-2">
      <introduction>
        <p> Use the given quadratic function, <m>f(x)=3(x-2)^2-4</m>, to answer the following: </p>
      </introduction>
      <task>
        <statement>
           <p> Applying <xref ref="vertex-form-of-a-quadratic-function"/>, what is the vertex and axis of symmetry of <m> f(x)</m>?</p>
        <ol marker="A." cols="1">
          <li><p> vertex: <m>(2,-4)</m>; axis of symmetry: <m>x=2</m> </p></li>
          <li><p> vertex: <m>(-2,4)</m>; axis of symmetry: <m>x=-2</m> </p></li>
          <li><p> vertex: <m>(-2,-4)</m>; axis of symmetry: <m>x=-2</m> </p></li>
          <li><p> vertex: <m>(2,4)</m>; axis of symmetry: <m>x=2</m></p></li>
      </ol>
    </statement>
    <answer>
      <p>
        A
      </p>
    </answer>
      </task>
      <task> 
        <statement>
          <p>Compare what you got in part <m>a</m> with the values you found in <xref ref="PR1-activity-1"/>. What do you notice? </p>
          </statement>
          <answer>
            <p>
              Students will probably notice that the vertex is also the minimum of the quadratic function and that the axis of symmetry goes through the minimum.
            </p>
          </answer>
      </task>
  </activity>

  <definition xml:id="standard-form-of-a-quadratic-function">
    <statement>
      <p> The <term>standard form</term> <idx><h>quadratic function</h><h>standard form</h></idx> of a quadratic function is given by <me>f(x)=ax^2+bx+c</me>, where <m>a, b </m>, and <m> c </m> are real coefficients.</p>
      <p> Just as with the vertex form of a quadratic, we can use the standard form of a quadratic to find the <term>axis of symmetry</term> <idx><h>quadratic function</h><h>axis of symmetry from standard form</h></idx> and the <term>vertex</term> <idx><h>quadratic function</h><h>vertex from standard form</h></idx>by using the values of <m>a, b </m>, and <m> c </m>. Given the standard form of a quadratic, the axis of symmetry is <m> x=\frac {-b}{2a}</m> and has a vertex at the point <m> (\frac{-b}{2a},f(\frac{-b}{2a}))</m>.
      </p>
    </statement>
  </definition>

  <activity xml:id="PR1-activity-3">
    <introduction>
      <p>Use the graph of the quadratic function to answer the questions below.</p>
    <figure width="100%" xml:id="PR1-quadratic-function-2">
      <image xml:id="PR1-quadratic-image-2">
        <description>Quadratic function that opens downward with vertex (-1,4)</description>
        <sageplot>
          f(x) = (-x^2-2*x+3)
          p=plot(f, (x, -4, 2),  ymin=-1, ymax=5, color='blue', thickness=3)
        </sageplot>
      </image>
    </figure>
    </introduction>
    <task> 
      <statement>
        <p> Which of the following quadratic functions could be the graph shown in the figure?
      <ol marker="A." cols="1">
        <li><p><m>f(x)=x^2+2x+3</m> </p></li>
        <li><p> <m>f(x)=-(x+1)^2+4</m> </p></li>
        <li><p> <m>f(x)=-x^2-2x+3</m> </p></li>
        <li><p> <m>f(x)=(x+1)^2+4</m></p></li>
    </ol>     
    </p>
    </statement>
    <answer>
      <p>
        B or C because they both have a negative in the front, which would indicate that the graph is pointing downward.
      </p>
    </answer>
    </task>
    <task> 
      <statement>
        <p> What is the maximum or minimum value? <ol marker="A." cols="2">
      <li><p><m>-1</m> </p></li>
      <li><p> <m>4</m> </p></li>
      <li><p> <m>-3</m> </p></li>
      <li><p> <m>1</m></p></li>
  </ol>     
  </p>
  </statement>
  <answer>
    <p>
      B. Instructors might need to distinguish what a max or min value is versus where the max or min value is located.
    </p>
  </answer>
  </task>
</activity>

  <activity xml:id="PR1-activity-4">
    <introduction>
      <p>Consider the following four graphs of quadratic functions:</p>
      <sbsgroup>
        <sidebyside width="50%">
          <image>
            <sageplot>
              f(x) = -2*(x+3)^2+1
              p=plot(f, (x, -7, 7), ymin=-7, ymax=7, color='blue', thickness=3) 
              p+=text('Graph A', (0, 8), fontsize=18, color='black')
              p
            </sageplot>
          </image>
          <image>
            <sageplot>
              f(x) = (x+3)^2+2
              p=plot(f, (x, -7, 7), ymin=-7, ymax=7, color='blue', thickness=3)
              p+=text('Graph B', (0, 8), fontsize=18, color='black')
              p
            </sageplot>
          </image>
        </sidebyside>
        <sidebyside width="50%">
          <image>
            <sageplot>
              f(x) = 1*(x-2)^2-3
              p=plot(f, (x, -7, 7), ymin=-7, ymax=7, color='blue', thickness=3)
              p+=text('Graph C', (0, 8), fontsize=18, color='black')
              p
            </sageplot>
          </image>
          <image>
            <sageplot>
              f(x) = -1*(x-2)^2+4
              p=plot(f, (x, -7, 7), ymin=-7, ymax=7, color='blue', thickness=3)
              p+=text('Graph D', (0, 8), fontsize=18, color='black')
              p
            </sageplot>
          </image>
        </sidebyside>
      </sbsgroup>
    </introduction>
    <task>
      <statement>
      <p>Which of the graphs above have a maximum?<ol marker="A." cols="2">
        <li><p> Graph A </p></li>
        <li><p> Graph B </p></li>
        <li><p> Graph C </p></li>
        <li><p> Graph D </p></li>
    </ol>
  </p>
    </statement>
    <answer>
      <p>
        A and D
      </p>
    </answer>
    </task>
    <task>
      <statement>
      <p>Which of the graphs above have a minimum?<ol marker="A." cols="2">
        <li><p> Graph A </p></li>
        <li><p> Graph B </p></li>
        <li><p> Graph C </p></li>
        <li><p> Graph D </p></li>
    </ol>
  </p>
    </statement>
    <answer>
      <p>
        B and C
      </p>
    </answer>
    </task>
    <task>
      <statement>
      <p>Which of the graphs above have an axis of symmetry at <m>x=2</m>? <ol marker="A." cols="2">
        <li><p> Graph A </p></li>
        <li><p> Graph B </p></li>
        <li><p> Graph C </p></li>
        <li><p> Graph D </p></li>
    </ol>
  </p>
</statement>
<answer>
  <p>
    C and D
  </p>
</answer>
</task>
  <task> 
    <statement>
      <p>Which of the graphs above represents the function <m>f(x)=-(x-2)^2+4</m>?
    <ol marker="A." cols="2">
      <li><p> Graph A </p></li>
      <li><p> Graph B </p></li>
      <li><p> Graph C </p></li>
      <li><p> Graph D </p></li>
  </ol>
</p>
    </statement>
    <answer>
      <p>
        D
      </p>
    </answer>
    </task>
    <task> 
      <statement>
        <p>Which of the graphs above represents the function <m>f(x)=x^2-4x+1</m>?
      <ol marker="A." cols="2">
        <li><p> Graph A </p></li>
        <li><p> Graph B </p></li>
        <li><p> Graph C </p></li>
        <li><p> Graph D </p></li>
    </ol>
  </p>
    </statement>
    <answer>
      <p>
        C
      </p>
    </answer>
    </task>
  </activity>

  <remark xml:id="remark-vertex-form-of-a-quadratic-function">
    <statement>
      <p> Notice that the maximum or minimum value of the quadratic function is the <m>y</m>-value of the vertex.
      </p>
    </statement>
  </remark>
  
  <activity xml:id="PR1-activity-5">
    <introduction>
      <p> A function <m>f(x)</m> has a maximum value at <m>7</m> and its axis of symmetry at <m>x=-2</m>.</p>
      </introduction>

        <task>
          <statement>
             <p> Sketch a graph of a function that meets the criteria for <m>f(x)</m>. </p>
             </statement>
             <answer>
              <p> Note that this is just one possible sketch students might draw.
                <figure width="100%" xml:id="possible-quadratic">
                  <image xml:id="one-possible-quadratic">
                    <description>A sketch of one possible quadratic that fits the criteria</description>
                    <sageplot>
                      f(x) = (-1*(x+2)^2+7)
                        p=plot(f, (x, -8, 5), ymin=-7, ymax=10, color='blue', thickness=3)
                    </sageplot>
                  </image>
                </figure>
              </p>
             </answer>
        </task>
        <task>
          <statement>
             <p> Was your graph the only possible answer? Try to sketch another graph that meets this criteria. </p>
             </statement>
             <answer>
              <p>
                No. There are many possible graphs students could sketch (think vertical shift along the axis of symmetry).
              </p>
             </answer>
        </task> 
</activity>

<remark xml:id="remark-using-zeros-to-graph-accurately">
  <statement>
    <p> Other points, such as <m>x</m>- and <m>y</m>-intercepts, may be helpful in sketching a more accurate graph of a quadratic function. 
    </p>
  </statement>
</remark>

<activity xml:id="PR1-activity-6">
  <introduction>
    <p>Consider the following two quadratic functions <m>f(x)=x^2-4x+20</m> and <m>g(x)=2x^2-8x+24</m> and answer the following questions:</p>
  </introduction>
  
  <task> 
    <statement>
    <p> Applying <xref ref="standard-form-of-a-quadratic-function"/>, what is the vertex and axis of symmetry of <m> f(x)</m>?</p>
    <ol marker="A." cols="1">
      <li><p> vertex: <m>(2,-16)</m>; axis of symmetry: <m>x=2</m> </p></li>
      <li><p> vertex: <m>(-2,16)</m>; axis of symmetry: <m>x=-2</m> </p></li>
      <li><p> vertex: <m>(-2,-16)</m>; axis of symmetry: <m>x=-2</m> </p></li>
      <li><p> vertex: <m>(2,16)</m>; axis of symmetry: <m>x=2</m></p></li>
  </ol>
  </statement>
  <answer>
    <p>
      D
    </p>
  </answer>
  </task>

  <task>
    <statement>
       <p> Applying <xref ref="standard-form-of-a-quadratic-function"/>, what is the vertex and axis of symmetry of <m> g(x)</m>?</p>
    <ol marker="A." cols="1">
      <li><p> vertex: <m>(2,-16)</m>; axis of symmetry: <m>x=2</m> </p></li>
      <li><p> vertex: <m>(-2,16)</m>; axis of symmetry: <m>x=-2</m> </p></li>
      <li><p> vertex: <m>(-2,-16)</m>; axis of symmetry: <m>x=-2</m> </p></li>
      <li><p> vertex: <m>(2,16)</m>; axis of symmetry: <m>x=2</m></p></li>
  </ol>
  </statement>
  <answer>
    <p>
      D
    </p>
  </answer>
  </task>
  
<task> 
  <statement>
    <p>What do you notice about <m>f(x)</m> and <m>g(x)</m>? 
</p>
  </statement>
  <answer>
    <p>
      They have the same vertex and axis of symmetry.
    </p>
  </answer>
  </task>
  <task> 
    <statement>
      <p> Now graph both <m>f(x)</m> and <m> g(x)</m> and draw a sketch of each graph on one coordinate plane. How are they similar/different?
</p>
  </statement>
  <answer>
    <p>
      By graphing the two functions, students should be able to see that although <m>f(x)</m> and <m>g(x)</m> have the same vertex and axis of symmetry, they are different functions/graphs. The graph of <m>g(x)</m> is "skinnier."
      <figure width="100%" xml:id="comparing-two-quadratic-graphs">
        <image xml:id="comparing-f-and-g">
          <sageplot>
            f(x) = (x^2-4*x+20)
            g(x) = (2*x^2-8*x+24)
              p=plot(f, (x, -3, 7), ymin=-2, ymax=30, color='blue', thickness=3)+ plot(g, (x, -3, 7), ymin=-2, ymax=30, color='green', thickness=3)
          </sageplot>
        </image>
      </figure>
    </p>
  </answer> 
  </task>
</activity>
